Target: `module/LLMWorkflow/governance/HumanReviewGates.ps1`

Reason:
- remove effectively double-suppressed module export behavior
- stop silently swallowing export-context failures with both `-ErrorAction SilentlyContinue` and an empty catch
- preserve dot-sourcing compatibility while making fallback behavior explicit and testable

---

## Patch A: replace silent module-export suppression at file end

Current code:

```powershell
try {
    Export-ModuleMember -Function @(
        ...
    ) -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
}
catch {
    # Silently ignore when dot-sourcing (not running as a module)
}
```

Replace with:

```powershell
if ($null -ne $MyInvocation.MyCommand.Module -or $ExecutionContext.SessionState.Module) {
    try {
        Export-ModuleMember -Function @(
            ...
        ) -ErrorAction Stop
    }
    catch {
        Write-Verbose "[HumanReviewGates] Export-ModuleMember failed: $($_.Exception.Message)"
    }
}
else {
    Write-Verbose "[HumanReviewGates] Skipping Export-ModuleMember because the file is being dot-sourced"
}
```

Why this is better:
- dot-sourced execution becomes an explicit branch instead of an exception-driven control path
- true export failures are no longer silently discarded
- behavior remains non-fatal for test files that dot-source the module

## Patch B: keep parse failures in `Get-ReviewHistory` as verbose, but make line context visible

Current code:

```powershell
catch {
    Write-Verbose "Failed to parse log entry: $_"
}
```

Recommended tightening:

```powershell
catch {
    Write-Verbose "[HumanReviewGates] Failed to parse review log entry: $($_.Exception.Message)"
}
```

This is not a behavior change so much as a diagnostics cleanup, but it keeps the failure signal consistent with the rest of the Priority 0 pass.
